<br>
I smoked over a pack a day for what... 6 years? and had been smoking prior to that as well (just not quite so heavily). What made me quit was a few things: One, I hated the smell. Two, I couldn't think of any GOOD reasons for me to keep doing it (aside from "It's a habit!", and that's an excuse... so is "I need it to relax!"), nor would my other half appreciate me smoking.<br>
<br>
Not to mention a 900-mile location change helped a lot, too. New places and people, and none of my old, familiar smoking habits.<br>
<br>
Smoke-free two years, now. :-)<br>
<br>
Edit: Forgot to mention that as soon as I convinced myself (and it didn't take too long to convince myself) that I didn't "need" them as I had no good reason for smoking them, I had no more cravings for them. It only took 2 days for my cravings to go away. Oddly enough, I had no headaches. <p><a href=http://www.livejournal.com/users/myschevious><img src=http://www.myschevious.net/christest.jpg></a></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub141.ezboard.com/beverquestpeople.showUserPublicProfile?gid=myscheviousmiamore>Myschevious MiAmore</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.myschevious.net/yahiko.gif" BORDER=0> at: 12/9/02 3:06:11 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#77839D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub141.ezboard.com/beverquestpeople.showUserPublicProfile?gid=groldar1>Groldar1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Familiar Face</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#F7E5C3>(12/9/02 4:26:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub141.ezboard.com/feverquestpeoplefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=699.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.gifs.net/animate/gallopani.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: must...quit...smoking... diary of a chickie quitting</span><hr size=1> I smoked a pack a day for 20 years and quit 5 years ago. Two things helped me<br>
<br>
1. Patches - I used the strongest patch for 3 months instead of stepping down as they suggest. After 3 months I was able to just quit putting patches on and it had been long enough to not feel like I needed to smoke.<br>
<br>
2. I had finally gotten it through my thick skull that smoking for me is like crack to a crack addict. I can never ever ever smoke again. Just one cig and Im a pack a day man within an hour. So whenever I started thinking ... hmmm well its been 6 months, I can smoke just one... I just think about how hard it was to get through those first weeks... wouldnt want to do that again for any reason.<br>
<br>
Just remember its tough but it is doable.<br>
